Here you can use any SortClause implementation. However, if you define the query in the view
configuration, you won't be able to instantiate the SortClause there. For that reason we provide a
way to define the sort clause as a string instead. We this format a subset of commonly used
SortClauses is supported. Sort direction is defined as ``asc`` for ascending and ``desc`` for
descending. In can be omitted, in which case it will default to ``asc``.

Strings can be used to define multiple sort clauses through an array of definitions:

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort:
        - depth asc
        - modified desc

Following sort clauses are available through string definition:

.. contents::
    :depth: 1
    :local:

Location depth
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

String ``depth`` enables sorting by Location's depth:

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: depth

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: depth asc

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: depth desc

Content Field
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

String in form of of ``field/[content_type]/[field]`` enables sorting by any Content Field. For
example by Field with identifier ``title`` in ContentType with identifier ``article``:

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: field/article/title

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: field/article/title asc

.. code-block:: yaml

    sort: field/article/title desc

